00:19:39,594 --> 00:19:40,644
Douche.

240
00:19:50,871 --> 00:19:52,805
(MUFFLED SINGING)

241
00:19:52,806 --> 00:19:55,542
Thank you very much.
You want olives in your salad?

242
00:19:55,543 --> 00:19:57,670
- HENRY: Yeah.
- Here you go. Watch this.

243
00:19:58,912 --> 00:20:00,607
(GRUNTING)

244
00:20:01,414 --> 00:20:02,674
Would you like some more?

245
00:20:04,217 --> 00:20:07,277
- What the...
- There he is. Hello.

246
00:20:09,556 --> 00:20:10,784
My card.

247
00:20:12,325 --> 00:20:14,555
We was afraid we'd have
to start without you.

248
00:20:15,328 --> 00:20:16,795
(SIGHS)

249
00:20:17,497 --> 00:20:18,589
This is a joke, right?

250
00:20:19,332 --> 00:20:21,072
WALTER: No, son, it's a fresh start.

251
00:20:21,134 --> 00:20:22,934
Have you completely lost your mind?

252
00:20:22,935 --> 00:20:25,371
- I know it seems a bit...
- I'm not talking to you, nut job.

253
00:20:25,372 --> 00:20:26,566
I'm talking to Mom.

254
00:20:27,774 --> 00:20:30,208
It takes you years to get him out of here,

255
00:20:30,276 --> 00:20:34,235
and you let him come back the next night
with a talking hamster?

256
00:20:38,206 --> 00:20:45,024
<i>JON STEWART: Failure on this scale
doesn't happen overnight.</i>

257
00:20:45,025 --> 00:20:47,855
MEREDITH: Still I can't believe
that you guys made that.

258
00:20:48,528 --> 00:20:51,326
I mean, you never... I mean, Walter never...

259
00:20:54,067 --> 00:20:57,298
I'm sorry. I'm not quite sure
how I'm supposed to address you.

260
00:20:58,304 --> 00:20:59,804
Well, you're doing fine, love.

261
00:21:00,539 --> 00:21:03,009
Well, tools were always
on your Christmas list,

262
00:21:03,042 --> 00:21:06,239
but I had no idea that you knew
how to actually make anything.

263
00:21:06,311 --> 00:21:08,176
He's a beaver, Mom. That's what they do.

264
00:21:08,247 --> 00:21:09,714
WALTER: Yeah. Spot on, mate.

265
00:21:10,215 --> 00:21:13,981
But, you know, Walter
wasn't half-bad himself, at one time.

266
00:21:14,053 --> 00:21:15,987
Yeah? Who taught him?

267
00:21:16,055 --> 00:21:17,855
WALTER: I suppose he taught himself.

268
00:21:18,090 --> 00:21:20,615
He was about your age, yeah. Cub Scouts.

269
00:21:20,616 --> 00:21:23,461
He and his pop were supposed
to make a racecar for a contest.

270
00:21:23,462 --> 00:21:26,329
Except, his pop weren't around
so he had to do it himself.

271
00:21:27,132 --> 00:21:28,793
Where was his dad?

272
00:21:34,139 --> 00:21:37,006
He got very sad and he had an accident.

273
00:21:37,109 --> 00:21:39,407
You mean Grandpa Jerry
from the graveyard?

274
00:21:40,112 --> 00:21:44,446
Right-o. Anyway, Walter had Grandpa's
tools but no clue how to use them.

275
00:21:45,384 --> 00:21:48,012
So, what he ended up making was so awful

276
00:21:48,013 --> 00:21:51,556
that it looked like he'd screwed a set
of wheels onto a piece of dog crap.

277
00:21:51,557 --> 00:21:52,683
(HENRY CHUCKLING)

278
00:21:52,758 --> 00:21:54,858
And you know what the other kids called it?

279
00:21:55,294 --> 00:21:58,820
The Turd. That was generous, mate.

280
00:21:59,163 --> 00:22:03,031
One lady threw up all over herself
just 'cause it got close to her.

281
00:22:03,835 --> 00:22:06,303
But when it came to racing...

282
00:22:07,071 --> 00:22:08,121
What?

283
00:22:08,873 --> 00:22:10,670
The Turd could not be beat.

284
00:22:11,075 --> 00:22:13,100
- Sweet.
- Yeah.

285
00:22:13,177 --> 00:22:14,804
- Dad?
- Yeah, mate?

286
00:22:15,847 --> 00:22:18,680
- Can we make a Turd?
- Yeah, any time, mate.

287
00:22:19,250 --> 00:22:21,445
You give the word, we'll make the Turd.

288
00:22:22,220 --> 00:22:23,270
Yeah.

289
00:22:25,022 --> 00:22:26,683
Good night, Beaver.

290
00:22:28,059 --> 00:22:29,109
Good night, mate.

291
00:22:29,660 --> 00:22:31,059
(KISSING)

292
00:22:36,400 --> 00:22:37,450
Good night.

293
00:22:40,271 --> 00:22:41,932
HENRY: Good night, Beaver.

294
00:22:43,941 --> 00:22:45,909
<i>- Hello?
- Norah.</i>

295
00:22:45,977 --> 00:22:47,308
Hey, it's Porter.

296
00:22:50,248 --> 00:22:52,011
Listen, what I said earlier...

297
00:22:52,083 --> 00:22:54,711
<i>- So, are you going to help me or not?
- Yeah.</i>

298
00:22:56,821 --> 00:23:03,248
But for this sort of thing, I'm going
to have to ask you for, like, $500?

299
00:23:04,094 --> 00:23:05,144
Done.

300
00:23:05,896 --> 00:23:08,262
Wow. Would you have gone $1,000?

301
00:23:08,263 --> 00:23:10,800
<i>- Oh, yeah.
- How about a million?</i>

302
00:23:10,801 --> 00:23:12,061
Can you come by tomorrow?

303
00:23:12,803 --> 00:23:15,601
Yeah! Yeah, yeah, yeah. Absolutely.

304
00:23:17,007 --> 00:23:21,774
You know, I didn't... Look, I...
We're cool, right? I... I'm...

305
00:23:21,775 --> 00:23:24,079
<i>You've never even said a word to me,
you know, and...</i>

306
00:23:24,080 --> 00:23:25,514
<i>- Porter?
- And it's not like we</i>

307
00:23:25,515 --> 00:23:28,765
<i>...know each other or anything... Yeah.
- Just come by tomorrow.</i>

308
00:23:29,786 --> 00:23:31,515
<i>- Okay.
- Okay.</i>

309
00:23:33,790 --> 00:23:35,587
WALTER: Good night! See you soon.

310
00:24:14,930 --> 00:24:16,830
(HUMMING)

311
00:24:40,222 --> 00:24:43,749
Trust me, mate. Today will set you free.

312
00:25:13,988 --> 00:25:15,421
What the hell is this?

313
00:25:15,490 --> 00:25:16,889
I have no idea.

314
00:25:16,958 --> 00:25:19,051
This is layoffs, isn't it? Goddamn China.

315
00:25:19,127 --> 00:25:20,867
WALTER: Nobody's getting laid off.

316
00:25:22,730 --> 00:25:23,780
Get rid of you lot?

317
00:25:24,065 --> 00:25:25,865
I'd have no one to boss around, yeah?

318
00:25:25,866 --> 00:25:30,437
- The boss woke up and brought a friend.
- (PEOPLE CHUCKLING)

319
00:25:30,438 --> 00:25:35,205
I think we should maintain some respect
until Mr. Black tells us...

320
00:25:35,576 --> 00:25:36,626
Good morning, all.

321
00:25:38,579 --> 00:25:40,479
I assume you all got the cards.

322
00:25:41,282 --> 00:25:43,876
If not, allow me to briefly explain.

323
00:25:44,886 --> 00:25:49,050
Walter Black ascended
to CEO of this company two years ago.

324
00:25:49,123 --> 00:25:54,584
Not through any particular skill or merit,
but because Walter was next in line

325
00:25:54,729 --> 00:25:59,257
rather than our infinitely more qualified VP
standing right here.

326
00:25:59,866 --> 00:26:00,916
Hello, love.

327
00:26:00,934 --> 00:26:05,166
It was a job Walter was, well,
ill-prepared to handle.

328
00:26:06,239 --> 00:26:07,638
Basically, well...

329
00:26:09,076 --> 00:26:10,600
Walter's been a loser.

330
00:26:11,678 --> 00:26:18,277
Which is why, as of now, he is resigning
and putting me in charge.

331
00:26:18,278 --> 00:26:22,855
So, before you decide to run me out on a rail
with all the flaming torches and pitchforks,

332
00:26:22,856 --> 00:26:28,988
hear me out, give me five minutes,
then you may tear me to shreds, if you like.

333
00:26:29,096 --> 00:26:33,829
First, I will be ceding control
of all individual projects

334
00:26:33,900 --> 00:26:35,390
back to the teams themselves.

335
00:26:35,469 --> 00:26:36,800
That means you will be free

336
00:26:36,903 --> 00:26:40,430
and entrusted to do the jobs
you was hired to do in the first place.

337
00:26:40,507 --> 00:26:41,557
Hello, Hank.

338
00:26:41,575 --> 00:26:45,238
Second, we will revamp,
revitalize, re-launch

339
00:26:45,412 --> 00:26:48,939
at the International Game
and Toy Manufacturers Expo

340
00:26:49,016 --> 00:26:51,780
in six weeks' time.

341
00:26:52,219 --> 00:26:57,179
Now, I know there's a very high degree
of skepticism about my ability to lead.

342
00:26:57,557 --> 00:26:58,819
Isn't that right?

343
00:26:58,892 --> 00:27:02,258
I mean, middle-aged man
with his arm stuck up my bum. Right?

344
00:27:02,495 --> 00:27:06,659
Who wouldn't doubt me?
But I'll make you the following deal.

345
00:27:06,732 --> 00:27:11,362
You give me two weeks, just two,
and at the end of that time,

346
00:27:11,437 --> 00:27:14,668
anyone who wants to resign
will receive severance pay

347
00:27:14,740 --> 00:27:16,970
and a glowing letter of recommendation.

348
00:27:17,043 --> 00:27:20,206
- No questions asked, no exceptions.
- MAN: Excuse me?

349
00:27:20,346 --> 00:27:22,266
And who exactly are you supposed to be?

350
00:27:22,548 --> 00:27:25,449
Bollocks. Did I forget to introduce meself?

351
00:27:26,052 --> 00:27:28,919
You may simply call me the Beaver.

352
00:27:36,729 --> 00:27:37,787
Impressive.

353
00:27:40,032 --> 00:27:41,412
So, what do you need to know?

354
00:27:42,768 --> 00:27:46,431
Well, I guess the first thing is,
what do you want to say?

355
00:27:49,408 --> 00:27:51,273
Well, that's kind of the problem.

356
00:27:51,610 --> 00:27:54,807
I mean, I got good grades. Big deal.
What do I know?

357
00:27:54,880 --> 00:27:58,646
Okay. Well, how do you want people to feel
when you're done?

358
00:27:58,918 --> 00:28:04,514
I guess I just want them to feel not

359
00:28:05,523 --> 00:28:06,785
let down.

360
00:28:06,925 --> 00:28:07,975
"Not let down."

361
00:28:08,426 --> 00:28:09,723
That's powerful.

362
00:28:11,329 --> 00:28:13,490
"I'm excited, pumped. How are you doing?"

363
00:28:13,565 --> 00:28:15,590
"Me? I'm not let down."

364
00:28:15,667 --> 00:28:16,793
(LAUGHS)

365
00:28:16,868 --> 00:28:19,666
I told you that I suck.
This is why I need you.

366
00:28:19,737 --> 00:28:23,264
Okay, well, you're a cheerleader,
notorious hothead.

367
00:28:23,341 --> 00:28:26,591
Could we talk about you getting expelled
from the eighth grade?

368
00:28:27,278 --> 00:28:28,838
How did you find out about that?

369
00:28:29,481 --> 00:28:31,574
No secrets on the Internet.

370
00:28:32,117 --> 00:28:33,167
What did you do?

371
00:28:33,168 --> 00:28:34,485
Did you steal some encyclopedias?

372
00:28:34,486 --> 00:28:36,511
- Chew some nicotine gum?
- No.

373
00:28:36,588 --> 00:28:38,488
What? Tease a fat kid?

374
00:28:39,023 --> 00:28:40,073
Shut up.

375
00:28:40,525 --> 00:28:41,725
All right. So, what is it?

376
00:28:44,229 --> 00:28:45,526
I was tagging.

377
00:28:48,233 --> 00:28:49,461
Tagging?

378
00:28:51,102 --> 00:28:52,296
Like...

379
00:28:56,007 --> 00:28:57,207
Like graffiti tagging?

380
00:28:57,542 --> 00:29:01,568
More like art. It was just illegal.

381
00:29:03,514 --> 00:29:06,972
Where's all this rebel-artist shit now?

382
00:29:07,518 --> 00:29:09,509
That was a long time ago.

383
00:29:10,387 --> 00:29:13,845
You still have some, don't you? Yeah.

384
00:29:14,057 --> 00:29:16,150
- Show me, please.
- No.

385
00:29:16,151 --> 00:29:20,596
If you show me, I will write you a speech
that you could free Tibet with.

386
00:29:20,597 --> 00:29:22,097
Why do you want to see it so bad?

387
00:29:22,966 --> 00:29:24,661
Because I like to be surprised.

388
00:29:29,473 --> 00:29:31,805
- We have to be quick.
- All right.

389
00:29:33,710 --> 00:29:35,439
Whose room is this?

390
00:29:35,746 --> 00:29:37,043
NORAH: No one's.

391
00:29:46,390 --> 00:29:47,584
Oh, wow.

392
00:29:58,168 --> 00:30:03,298
I like to do it big.
Like freeways, buildings, billboards.

393
00:30:04,607 --> 00:30:09,738
And fast.
Like I'm running a million miles an hour.

394
00:30:11,581 --> 00:30:13,105
No thinking, you know?

395
00:30:15,585 --> 00:30:16,813
Why did you stop?

396
00:30:20,590 --> 00:30:24,048
'Cause I got caught
and my mom couldn't take it.

397
00:30:24,927 --> 00:30:27,896
Anyway, I threw them all away.

398
00:30:27,964 --> 00:30:29,404
Someone must have liked them.

399
00:30:30,433 --> 00:30:33,266
Pulled them out of the trash, didn't they?

400
00:30:34,503 --> 00:30:37,213
- Who was it?
- NORAH'S MOM: What are you doing in here?

401
00:30:38,808 --> 00:30:41,709
I was just showing Porter around the house.

402
00:30:43,579 --> 00:30:45,809
He's on the math team with me.

403
00:30:46,282 --> 00:30:48,011
- Right.
- Time to go.

404
00:30:51,187 --> 00:30:53,985
Hey, I'm sorry about my mom.

405
00:30:55,124 --> 00:30:57,319
- She's just, you know...
- That's fine.

406
00:31:01,930 --> 00:31:03,693
You know, you are

407
00:31:05,834 --> 00:31:07,233
so much weirder...

408
00:31:10,705 --> 00:31:14,232
Not weird, I just mean, like,
different, I guess.

409
00:31:14,843 --> 00:31:18,244
You're a lot more different
than I thought you'd be.

410
00:31:18,245 --> 00:31:21,548
You know, for someone I'm paying
a lot of money to write a speech for me,

411
00:31:21,549 --> 00:31:23,039
you're not very articulate.

412
00:31:24,152 --> 00:31:25,352
I'm much better on paper.

413
00:31:26,421 --> 00:31:27,752
We'll see.

414
00:31:28,890 --> 00:31:32,758
Thank you for not laughing, I guess.

415
00:31:33,228 --> 00:31:34,278
I wouldn't do that.

416
00:31:34,496 --> 00:31:36,123
I wouldn't laugh.

417
00:31:37,032 --> 00:31:38,090
Good.

418
00:31:40,568 --> 00:31:42,160
Very, very good.

419
00:31:45,340 --> 00:31:48,138
<i>(SWIM UNTIL YOU CAN'T
SEE LANDPLAYING)</i>

420
00:31:57,185 --> 00:32:02,281
<i>(SINGING) We salute at the threshold
of the North Sea in my mind</i>

421
00:32:03,057 --> 00:32:06,322
<i>And a nod to the boredom
that drove me here</i>

422
00:32:06,393 --> 00:32:10,454
<i>To face the tide and swim</i>

423
00:32:11,165 --> 00:32:15,192
<i>I swim, oh, swim</i>

424
00:32:15,469 --> 00:32:19,701
<i>WALTER: (AS BEAVER) And, eventually,
what seems strange becomes common.</i>

425
00:32:20,841 --> 00:32:23,969
<i>What seemed impossible becomes real.</i>

426
00:32:24,044 --> 00:32:29,277
<i>(SINGING) Up to my knees now,
do I wait? Do I dive?</i>

427
00:32:29,950 --> 00:32:34,910
<i>The sea has seen my like before though
it's my first and perhaps last time</i>

428
00:32:35,856 --> 00:32:41,226
<i>Let's call me a Baptist,
call this the drowning of the past</i>

429
00:32:41,662 --> 00:32:46,861
<i>She's there on the shoreline
Throwing stones at my back</i>

430
00:32:46,934 --> 00:32:50,335
<i>So swim until you can't see land</i>

431
00:32:50,404 --> 00:32:53,202
<i>Swim until you can't see land</i>

432
00:32:53,273 --> 00:32:56,367
<i>Swim until you can't see land</i>

433
00:32:56,443 --> 00:33:00,174
<i>Are you a man or are you a bag of sand?</i>

434
00:33:02,782 --> 00:33:06,932
<i>WALTER: (AS BEAVER) Until things almost
start to feel the way they used to.</i>

435
00:33:08,350 --> 00:33:11,356
Fixed it, love. Working like a charm.

436
00:33:11,357 --> 00:33:13,552
<i>It's like it's all brand new.</i>

437
00:33:20,967 --> 00:33:22,017
(HAMMERING)

438
00:33:22,068 --> 00:33:25,595
- Walter. Walter, wake up. Wake up.
- Mmm. What?

439
00:33:25,596 --> 00:33:29,474
It's Henry. He snuck out of his room.
He's down in the garage again by himself.

440
00:33:29,475 --> 00:33:31,705
Well, tell him to come to bed.

441
00:33:31,778 --> 00:33:36,613
I know. I tell him every night, but he needs
to hear it from, you know, you.

442
00:33:37,583 --> 00:33:38,633
Yeah.

443
00:33:40,653 --> 00:33:41,984
I'm on it.

444
00:33:45,792 --> 00:33:48,989
Whoa, where are you going
this time of night?

445
00:33:48,990 --> 00:33:51,329
I'm gonna tell the little guy
to knock it off so I can sleep.

446
00:33:51,330 --> 00:33:52,380
Right.

447
00:33:52,432 --> 00:33:55,799
I was going to the same place.
Come on. Let's triple-team him.

448
00:33:56,769 --> 00:33:59,932
That's okay.
You've got your little furry friend.

449
00:34:03,074 --> 00:34:04,124
Good night.

450
00:34:13,452 --> 00:34:15,312
What are you making besides a racket?

451
00:34:15,320 --> 00:34:16,760
You couldn't sleep, either?

452
00:34:17,222 --> 00:34:20,453
Well, actually, mate,
I was having a brilliant kip

453
00:34:20,525 --> 00:34:22,720
till you started banging away.

454
00:34:23,562 --> 00:34:25,427
I just had this idea.

455
00:34:25,497 --> 00:34:28,027
Oh, yeah?
Well, let's have the idea in the morning.

456
00:34:28,567 --> 00:34:31,092
Just 10 more minutes, please?

457
00:34:31,169 --> 00:34:32,796
Ten more minutes, all right, yes.

458
00:34:32,871 --> 00:34:37,308
But no more mucking about with tools
when I'm not around. It's not safe.

459
00:34:37,476 --> 00:34:40,138
Or when your mother's asked you not to.
Or at night.

460
00:34:40,212 --> 00:34:44,080
Or in a toilet.
Or when you're climbing Mount Everest.

461
00:34:44,583 --> 00:34:46,141
Or picking your nose. Agreed?

462
00:34:46,751 --> 00:34:48,616
- Agreed.
- There you go.

463
00:34:51,356 --> 00:34:54,519
Can you talk to me? I like it when you talk.

464
00:34:55,460 --> 00:34:57,080
What do you want me to talk about?

465
00:34:57,095 --> 00:34:58,562
Doesn't matter. Just talk.

466
00:35:00,131 --> 00:35:02,030
You have a funny voice.

467
00:35:03,033 --> 00:35:05,373
You're quite easily entertained, aren't you?

468
00:35:08,973 --> 00:35:13,467
Give you a buzz saw, a block of wood,
and some chatter...

469
00:35:20,484 --> 00:35:22,042
(WALTER HUMMING)

470
00:35:22,043 --> 00:35:24,320
MEREDITH: Hey, Walter, did you talk to him?

471
00:35:24,321 --> 00:35:27,290
Yes, and everything's fine.
He'll stick to the schedule.

472
00:35:27,558 --> 00:35:28,684
What's going on?

473
00:35:28,826 --> 00:35:32,455
I've had a breakthrough, love.
Got to get to work right away.

474
00:35:32,563 --> 00:35:33,613
Now?

475
00:35:33,631 --> 00:35:35,189
Not a moment to spare!

476
00:35:38,502 --> 00:35:40,197
You're a goddess.

477
00:35:52,449 --> 00:35:54,883
Sir? You're in early.

478
00:35:54,952 --> 00:35:57,250
Just the woman I wanted to see.

479
00:35:58,322 --> 00:35:59,372
Have a look at this.

480
00:36:00,424 --> 00:36:03,221
Now, we need to get started on this
right away.

481
00:36:03,760 --> 00:36:05,193
It's a beaver?

482
00:36:06,262 --> 00:36:07,312
It's the future.

483
00:36:07,764 --> 00:36:08,814
This?

484
00:36:09,032 --> 00:36:11,322
WALTER: The Talking Beaver
Woodworking Set.

485
00:36:11,568 --> 00:36:14,366
You get your basic tools, a block of wood

486
00:36:14,437 --> 00:36:17,027
and a talking beaver
to work right alongside of you.

487
00:36:17,028 --> 00:36:18,840
You should see the kids, love.

488
00:36:18,841 --> 00:36:20,976
I mean, they've got their cell phones
and their computers,

489
00:36:20,977 --> 00:36:23,612
but, wow, you give them a block of wood,
a hammer and a saw?

490
00:36:23,613 --> 00:36:25,013
Bob's their bleeding auntie.

491
00:36:25,014 --> 00:36:27,616
Their poor little brains are starving
for something like this.

492
00:36:27,617 --> 00:36:31,018
So, you're talking about a new product line
for what? Christmas?

493
00:36:31,087 --> 00:36:34,056
Christmas? I'm talking about right now,
woman. Today.

494
00:36:34,791 --> 00:36:36,258
This morning.

495
00:36:37,360 --> 00:36:40,190
I guess there could be an ancillary market
in more tools.

496
00:36:40,797 --> 00:36:42,697
Maybe pre-cut lumber pieces?

497
00:36:42,765 --> 00:36:44,790
Sort of like Lego kits but made of wood.

498
00:36:44,867 --> 00:36:47,495
And you can work them
into shapes on your own.

499
00:36:47,770 --> 00:36:49,965
Now, that's using your scone.

500
00:36:50,306 --> 00:36:52,286
Not just made out of wood, is it? Let's go.

501
00:36:52,542 --> 00:36:53,922
But this would mean, I mean,

502
00:36:53,943 --> 00:36:57,777
even if we could get one ready in time,
this is all we would have for the Expo.

503
00:36:58,081 --> 00:36:59,761
That's all we'll need, my darling.

504
00:37:07,116 --> 00:37:12,159
<i>WALTER: (AS BEAVER)
And for every person that points out</i>

505
00:37:12,160 --> 00:37:14,061
<i>that there's a rodent at the helm,</i>

506
00:37:14,062 --> 00:37:19,625
<i>there's another to remind him or her that
production has already increased by 35%.</i>

507
00:37:20,002 --> 00:37:23,802
<i>At the end of those first two weeks,
not one person resigns.</i>

508
00:37:24,306 --> 00:37:25,356
<i>Not one.</i>

509
00:37:27,109 --> 00:37:29,029
WALTER: Now, we're going to start with...

510
00:37:30,178 --> 00:37:34,410
The Beaver, as a core item,
along with endless project kits

511
00:37:34,883 --> 00:37:36,748
could produce an exponential return.

512
00:37:37,185 --> 00:37:41,554
<i>The question is, do we want
to continue struggling merely to survive,</i>

513
00:37:41,623 --> 00:37:46,526
or do we want to embrace something new,
something different,

514
00:37:46,628 --> 00:37:48,687
<i>and see where it takes us?</i>

515
00:37:52,100 --> 00:37:55,230
<i>WALTER: (AS BEAVER) Once again,
our beloved Jerry Co.</i>

516
00:37:55,303 --> 00:37:59,501
has vision, power, energy, balls.

517
00:38:02,244 --> 00:38:05,794
Item number three this morning,
we've got some fabrication concerns.

518
00:38:05,980 --> 00:38:07,379
Why are you all laughing?

519
00:38:39,880 --> 00:38:41,438
(PANTING)

520
00:38:48,122 --> 00:38:50,556
Did you talk to Dr. Macy today?

521
00:38:52,226 --> 00:38:56,890
Indeed. He says we're coming along
just brilliantly.

522
00:38:56,891 --> 00:39:04,069
Well, did he give you some kind of a
timeline for when the treatment might be over?

523
00:39:04,070 --> 00:39:06,402
No, nothing specific, love.

524
00:39:06,473 --> 00:39:08,600
Like a week, or a month, or...

525
00:39:09,642 --> 00:39:10,904
It's a process, love.

526
00:39:11,644 --> 00:39:13,703
We'll know when the time is right.

527
00:39:16,483 --> 00:39:19,418
Now, rest up, you delicious little tart.

528
00:39:19,486 --> 00:39:21,920
There's more where that came from.

529
00:39:56,022 --> 00:39:59,788
Hector, what do I always say, man?
Read it before you turn it in.

530
00:39:59,789 --> 00:40:01,527
It was about your own family,
for Christ's sake.

531
00:40:01,528 --> 00:40:04,495
I just figured since it was personal,
there wouldn't be no test questions on it.

532
00:40:04,496 --> 00:40:07,659
- But your own grandma turned you in.
- Yes. She was so proud.

533
00:40:07,733 --> 00:40:11,692
Talking about the stuff that you had wrote
about her back in the day in D.R.

534
00:40:11,693 --> 00:40:14,472
And then all of a sudden,
she could just tell I knew nothing about it.

535
00:40:14,473 --> 00:40:16,707
So, she starts crying.
She calls the principal, says she doesn't...

536
00:40:16,708 --> 00:40:18,810
All right. My name stays out of this.
You understand that, right?

537
00:40:18,811 --> 00:40:22,542
- She called me a liar and a cheater.
- All right, all right, all right. Look.

538
00:40:22,915 --> 00:40:27,118
Okay, I'm gonna make
a dummy website, all right?

539
00:40:27,119 --> 00:40:29,320
You tell them you sent in your money,
you got your paper.

540
00:40:29,321 --> 00:40:31,346
That's all you know, okay?

541
00:40:32,226 --> 00:40:34,592
Hector, look, I gotta go.

542
00:40:34,593 --> 00:40:36,661
I'm gonna give you the website tomorrow,
all right?

543
00:40:36,662 --> 00:40:38,789
- Hector!
- Yes, yes, yes.

544
00:40:38,864 --> 00:40:40,195
Great. Good.

545
00:40:40,866 --> 00:40:41,924
Norah!

546
00:40:42,634 --> 00:40:43,692
- Hey.
- Hey.

547
00:40:45,337 --> 00:40:48,067
- Why are you all sweaty?
- I was doing yoga.

548
00:40:48,807 --> 00:40:51,469
- Manly.
- Downward Dog's a bitch.

549
00:40:53,612 --> 00:40:56,376
- Are you busy tonight?
- Are you asking me out?

550
00:40:56,715 --> 00:40:57,765
No. Not at all.

551
00:40:57,783 --> 00:41:01,014
I was just gonna casually inquire
if you're busy

552
00:41:01,015 --> 00:41:04,354
without making it seem like I'd been
up all night planning something elaborate.

553
00:41:04,355 --> 00:41:07,305
Have you been up all night
planning something elaborate?

554
00:41:07,306 --> 00:41:09,626
Yeah, I have, like, maps and stuff.

555
00:41:09,627 --> 00:41:10,677
(LAUGHS)

556
00:41:11,829 --> 00:41:15,094
You can pick me up at 7:00.
I have to be back at 12:00.

557
00:41:16,100 --> 00:41:19,900
Awesome, so it's a date.
I mean, it is, right?

558
00:41:20,838 --> 00:41:22,169
We'll see.

559
00:41:25,343 --> 00:41:26,393
Cool.

560
00:41:28,779 --> 00:41:30,508
Don't mess this up.

561
00:41:58,175 --> 00:42:00,234
You let me lead, all right?

562
00:42:01,078 --> 00:42:03,602
Are you almost ready? Reservation's at 8:00.

563
00:42:04,881 --> 00:42:09,716
- Bloody hell, woman. Look at you.
- Well, you're looking pretty good yourself.

564
00:42:09,717 --> 00:42:12,087
- Yeah, well, you ain't seen nothing yet.
- Yeah?

565
00:42:12,088 --> 00:42:14,613
The girls whipped up
something special for me.

566
00:42:17,627 --> 00:42:19,925
We're talking full-on tux, love.

567
00:42:21,698 --> 00:42:24,599
Yeah. Just give us a minute to pop it on,
and we'll be off.

568
00:42:24,668 --> 00:42:26,693
Wait, it's our anniversary, honey.

569
00:42:26,694 --> 00:42:28,437
That's why I went for the penguin suit.

570
00:42:28,438 --> 00:42:31,448
I do not want to celebrate
20 years of marriage with a puppet.

571
00:42:33,443 --> 00:42:37,402
I'm sorry. I've been very patient
and I've been very supportive,

572
00:42:38,548 --> 00:42:41,176
but I want you, not him.

573
00:42:43,486 --> 00:42:45,920
Not tonight.

574
00:42:55,565 --> 00:42:56,615
Hi.

575
00:42:57,767 --> 00:42:59,530
Black, party of two.

576
00:43:12,281 --> 00:43:15,182
So, when do I get
to see some of your pages?

577
00:43:16,218 --> 00:43:17,742
Never. It's a pyramid scheme.

578
00:43:17,743 --> 00:43:20,188
- I didn't tell you that?
- No.

579
00:43:20,189 --> 00:43:22,521
You didn't get the brochure?

580
00:43:22,591 --> 00:43:25,389
- I'm kidding. I'll get it done.
- You better.

581
00:43:25,461 --> 00:43:29,693
I'm not giving you 500 bucks just so you can
buy a flat screen for your dorm room.

582
00:43:29,765 --> 00:43:32,495
I'm not buying a flat screen
for my dorm room.

583
00:43:32,568 --> 00:43:33,618
Then, what?

584
00:43:34,636 --> 00:43:36,331
- A mummy.
- No mummy.

585
00:43:37,573 --> 00:43:40,474
- Then, what? What's it going to?
- Nothing.

586
00:43:41,243 --> 00:43:42,574
Mmm-mmm.

587
00:43:42,644 --> 00:43:45,704
A guy like you
doesn't do anything for no reason.

588
00:43:45,781 --> 00:43:47,442
You've got a plan.

589
00:43:54,523 --> 00:43:59,426
I was listening to the radio and, apparently,
it's gonna be really hot this weekend.

590
00:44:00,396 --> 00:44:04,661
Not hot-hot, just above average.

591
00:44:08,803 --> 00:44:12,034
- So, how's work?
- Good. Yeah, busy.

592
00:44:13,508 --> 00:44:14,558
Busy?

593
00:44:15,737 --> 00:44:21,748
NORAH: Maps? That's what
you're saving all your money for?

594
00:44:21,749 --> 00:44:22,807
Yeah.

595
00:44:22,808 --> 00:44:26,119
Okay, explain, because right now, it's
looking like where you hide your bodies.

596
00:44:26,120 --> 00:44:30,181
- It is. Every red dot is a dead body.
- (LAUGHING)

597
00:44:30,182 --> 00:44:31,658
Just trying to be honest.

598
00:44:31,659 --> 00:44:33,820
Okay, really, what's it for?

599
00:44:36,364 --> 00:44:40,801
It's, like, all these places where
everything changed in the blink of an eye.

600
00:44:40,802 --> 00:44:44,037
Like the balcony
where Martin Luther King got shot.

601
00:44:44,038 --> 00:44:47,228
The train tracks where Woody Guthrie
hopped on his first train.

602
00:44:47,642 --> 00:44:48,692
And?

603
00:44:52,046 --> 00:44:56,278
And I just visit them and then I end up
at Brown the day before school starts.

604
00:44:57,151 --> 00:44:59,619
It's kind of like a find-yourself trip?

605
00:45:00,121 --> 00:45:04,489
No. More like a lose-stuff trip.

606
00:45:06,093 --> 00:45:08,789
What kind of stuff do you want to lose?

607
00:45:09,696 --> 00:45:12,028
At last count, 49 things.

608
00:45:16,036 --> 00:45:20,268
An elaborate, mysterious plan,
and a little weird.

609
00:45:22,742 --> 00:45:23,792
But I like it.

610
00:45:24,511 --> 00:45:27,241
It's your paper-writing dollars at work.

611
00:45:35,922 --> 00:45:36,972
What was that for?

612
00:45:37,390 --> 00:45:39,324
You said you liked to be surprised.

613
00:45:41,928 --> 00:45:44,021
- Ready?
- For what?

614
00:45:58,044 --> 00:45:59,739
It's a great place.

615
00:46:00,780 --> 00:46:03,340
It's kind of scary but beautiful.

616
00:46:05,818 --> 00:46:09,720
Look, I wasn't sure which color you liked,
so I kind of got everything.

617
00:46:09,788 --> 00:46:11,881
I hope you like sunburst yellow.

618
00:46:12,758 --> 00:46:15,318
Porter? Porter, come on.
What are you doing?

619
00:46:15,661 --> 00:46:17,322
Is this fantastic, or what?

620
00:46:17,396 --> 00:46:20,406
Are you kidding?
It's awesome, but I'm not going to touch it.

621
00:46:20,633 --> 00:46:22,601
- Why not?
- Because.

622
00:46:24,403 --> 00:46:27,861
- Because, what? Why not?
- Because I don't want to.

623
00:46:29,542 --> 00:46:32,252
Come on, Norah.
You have this amazing thing that you do.

624
00:46:32,945 --> 00:46:37,041
You just put all of yourself out there.
All I can do is sound like other people.

625
00:46:37,950 --> 00:46:39,940
- I know you have something to say.
- Okay.

626
00:46:40,119 --> 00:46:43,520
- Knock yourself out. You do it.
- Come on.

627
00:46:44,723 --> 00:46:46,418
No. I don't paint.

628
00:46:47,126 --> 00:46:50,061
Why not?
You're so good at being other people.

629
00:46:50,129 --> 00:46:54,156
- Well, maybe if I could paint I would, but...
- Porter, just start.

630
00:46:55,634 --> 00:46:56,726
Okay.

631
00:47:00,673 --> 00:47:03,563
What are you going to do?
Write "Norah + Porter forever"?

632
00:47:05,043 --> 00:47:07,068
Because that'd be pretty cute.

633
00:47:37,442 --> 00:47:38,636
Right?

634
00:47:43,047 --> 00:47:45,982
- That's what you've been wanting to say.
- No.

635
00:47:46,050 --> 00:47:49,178
You wrote 400 pages of notes.
Not one word about him?

636
00:47:49,179 --> 00:47:51,755
What happened to my brother
is none of your business.

637
00:47:51,756 --> 00:47:52,806
Do you understand?

638
00:47:52,807 --> 00:47:54,758
I just thought there was something
you wanted to say

639
00:47:54,759 --> 00:47:56,727
and you didn't know how.

640
00:47:57,695 --> 00:47:59,015
It's none of your business.

641
00:47:59,964 --> 00:48:02,314
What kind of person
does something like this?

642
00:48:02,667 --> 00:48:04,362
What's the matter with you?

643
00:48:08,772 --> 00:48:09,966
(SIREN WAILS)

644
00:48:20,150 --> 00:48:21,549
Go on. Open it.

645
00:48:22,986 --> 00:48:25,921
Henry helped me, which basically means

646
00:48:26,023 --> 00:48:29,220
that I bought the wood
and he did all the work.

647
00:48:35,132 --> 00:48:36,827
It's a memory box.

648
00:48:38,035 --> 00:48:39,730
It's very nice. Thank you.

649
00:48:40,370 --> 00:48:41,769
Look inside.

650
00:48:47,277 --> 00:48:50,804
I thought it was important
to remind ourselves of how things were.

651
00:48:50,947 --> 00:48:53,609
How things should be.

652
00:48:56,987 --> 00:48:58,852
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

653
00:49:05,194 --> 00:49:08,459
Walter. No, no, no. It's okay. It's okay.

654
00:49:09,131 --> 00:49:10,962
(PANTING)

655
00:49:12,335 --> 00:49:13,893
Is this what you want?

656
00:49:14,737 --> 00:49:17,069
Is this progress? Christ, woman!

657
00:49:18,240 --> 00:49:20,970
He's suffering from depression,
not amnesia!

658
00:49:20,971 --> 00:49:23,611
You think the problem
is he can't remember these things?

659
00:49:23,612 --> 00:49:26,410
- No.
- He can't go back. Don't you see that?

660
00:49:27,350 --> 00:49:31,616
This is all in the past, and dredging
it up... Do you know where this leads?

661
00:49:32,288 --> 00:49:34,620
You know where this Walter goes?

662
00:49:34,690 --> 00:49:39,252
To a 10th floor balcony,
tied to a shower curtain rod.

663
00:49:39,328 --> 00:49:41,228
Is that what you want?

664
00:49:42,164 --> 00:49:45,292
You want the rest of your life
to be just like tonight?

665
00:49:45,368 --> 00:49:48,963
- Well, that was Walter.
- No, Walter. No, come on.

666
00:49:50,673 --> 00:49:53,301
Look at this. You really look at this.

667
00:49:55,211 --> 00:49:56,769
That's you, Walter.

668
00:49:57,980 --> 00:49:59,470
Remember that?

669
00:50:00,449 --> 00:50:05,408
When Porter was born, and he was so little?

670
00:50:06,020 --> 00:50:09,649
And they pulled him out of me,
and you stood right by him.

671
00:50:09,650 --> 00:50:10,858
You looked him right in the eye,

672
00:50:10,859 --> 00:50:12,626
and you let him know
that you weren't going anywhere,

673
00:50:12,627 --> 00:50:15,577
that you were staying right there
so he wouldn't be scared.

674
00:50:17,065 --> 00:50:20,135
Walter, that's you. That's the man I love.
That's the man I need.

675
00:50:22,237 --> 00:50:23,917
You're still inside there, honey.

676
00:50:25,373 --> 00:50:29,605
I know you're in there. We can go back.

677
00:50:29,606 --> 00:50:31,545
We can get back to the way
that we used to be.

678
00:50:31,546 --> 00:50:34,276
We are not going
down that street again, Meredith.

679
00:50:35,383 --> 00:50:39,649
This man is a dead end.
He's gone. He has to be.

680
00:50:40,522 --> 00:50:41,572
You get it?

681
00:50:42,690 --> 00:50:43,740
I fought for you.

682
00:50:43,741 --> 00:50:47,561
I practically breathed for you for two years
when you couldn't even get out of bed,

683
00:50:47,562 --> 00:50:50,656
and I will continue to fight for you
because I love you.

684
00:50:51,599 --> 00:50:54,789
I've got to know that you're coming back.
Come back to me, please.

685
00:50:55,503 --> 00:50:56,697
Walter?

686
00:50:56,771 --> 00:50:58,329
(CELL PHONE VIBRATING)

687
00:50:58,406 --> 00:50:59,668
Walter?

688
00:51:13,187 --> 00:51:15,985
Norah, I can't take this again.

689
00:51:19,626 --> 00:51:20,854
Come on.

690
00:51:29,002 --> 00:51:31,493
Hello. We came as soon as we heard.

691
00:51:32,773 --> 00:51:36,174
I'm the Beaver,
and this is Porter's dad, Walter.

692
00:51:36,175 --> 00:51:41,414
Listen, we'll get it all sorted.
I'm here now so we'll take care of things.

693
00:51:41,415 --> 00:51:43,610
Have a nice safe drive home.

694
00:52:00,100 --> 00:52:01,150
WALTER: Wait.

695
00:52:04,204 --> 00:52:07,502
Porter, mate, hang about. Come on.
We can discuss this. Come on.

696
00:52:07,503 --> 00:52:09,107
- Give me that thing!
- Calm down!

697
00:52:09,108 --> 00:52:11,406
- Give it to me! Goddamn it!
- Stop it!

698
00:52:11,477 --> 00:52:13,035
- Give me that thing!
- Stop!

699
00:52:13,112 --> 00:52:14,704
Leave him alone!

700
00:52:14,780 --> 00:52:15,906
(GRUNTS)

701
00:52:16,349 --> 00:52:21,150
Porter! Porter! Oh, my God.
Porter, are you okay? Are you all right?

702
00:52:21,151 --> 00:52:23,221
Porter, let me see your hands.
Are they bleeding?

703
00:52:23,222 --> 00:52:25,816
I'm sorry, son. I didn't mean to do that.

704
00:52:25,892 --> 00:52:27,985
You keep your hands off him!

705
00:52:28,661 --> 00:52:29,958
Porter, come on. Let me see.

706
00:52:44,143 --> 00:52:45,583
MEREDITH: Are you happy now?

707
00:52:45,845 --> 00:52:47,278
Porter? Porter?

708
00:53:26,384 --> 00:53:28,579
<i>It's Christmas in May.</i>

709
00:53:28,580 --> 00:53:30,654
<i>That's what some retailers are saying</i>

710
00:53:30,655 --> 00:53:34,648
<i>with Mr. Beaver Woodchopper Kits
selling out in droves.</i>

711
00:53:34,726 --> 00:53:37,820
<i>Recently, Jerry Co.
had been in steep decline,</i>

712
00:53:37,896 --> 00:53:41,229
<i>hovering on the verge of bankruptcy
earlier this year.</i>

713
00:53:41,333 --> 00:53:45,360
<i>But thanks to Mr. Beaver,
that won't be happening any time soon.</i>

714
00:53:46,638 --> 00:53:50,472
It's like a $100 million
ad campaign, for free!

715
00:53:51,843 --> 00:53:52,969
(SIGHS)

716
00:53:53,712 --> 00:53:58,115
Jerry Co.'s back in the game.
The old man would be so proud.

717
00:54:00,385 --> 00:54:01,647
I've got to hand it to you.

718
00:54:01,720 --> 00:54:04,917
You pulled all the strings,
and look where we landed.

719
00:54:04,990 --> 00:54:06,854
On top, for once.

720
00:54:11,328 --> 00:54:13,592
- It feels good, doesn't it?
- They.

721
00:54:17,701 --> 00:54:18,751
Sir?

722
00:54:20,270 --> 00:54:21,601
My family.

723
00:54:22,539 --> 00:54:25,309
Who's the biggest interview request
we've had so far?

724
00:54:28,012 --> 00:54:32,278
<i>- All the morning shows. CNN, CNBC...
- Today Show, then. Set it up.</i>

725
00:54:32,349 --> 00:54:36,115
<i>But, sir,
the Today Show is on television.</i>

726
00:54:36,186 --> 00:54:42,557
What are we hiding? We're winners.
We should be shouting it from the rooftops.

727
00:54:43,527 --> 00:54:45,154
It would certainly be a story.

728
00:54:54,204 --> 00:54:59,107
I'm gonna tell you something
that I've never told anyone else,

729
00:55:01,311 --> 00:55:02,991
but I think you're ready to hear it.

730
00:55:04,982 --> 00:55:06,074
Okay.

731
00:55:09,185 --> 00:55:10,379
I'm not a puppet.

732
00:55:13,823 --> 00:55:15,085
I'm real.

733
00:55:17,293 --> 00:55:18,624
I'm alive.

734
00:55:19,662 --> 00:55:21,857
And the world needs to know.

735
00:55:41,217 --> 00:55:42,417
(WALTER CLEARS THROAT)

736
00:55:43,686 --> 00:55:45,449
You all right, love?

737
00:55:48,791 --> 00:55:50,258
Some trouble?

738
00:55:51,027 --> 00:55:53,154
I talked to Dr. Macy today.

739
00:55:55,298 --> 00:55:57,823
What did he have to say for himself?

740
00:56:03,606 --> 00:56:06,336
He says that you haven't been to see him
in over a year.

741
00:56:06,337 --> 00:56:10,377
Dr. Macy says that you're sick, Walter.
Very sick.

742
00:56:10,378 --> 00:56:11,436
Yeah. Right.

743
00:56:11,437 --> 00:56:13,481
He said this sounds like
some kind of a mania.

744
00:56:13,482 --> 00:56:16,576
Okay, well, who gives a shit
what Dr. Macy has to say?

745
00:56:16,651 --> 00:56:17,701
I fixed him.

746
00:56:18,653 --> 00:56:23,420
Everybody else seems to get it.
Henry, people at work. Everyone except you.

747
00:56:23,421 --> 00:56:25,793
Does that tell you something?

748
00:56:25,794 --> 00:56:28,062
You just want to live like this forever?
Talking through your hand?

749
00:56:28,063 --> 00:56:31,031
I'd say it's been a pretty
smashing success so far, wouldn't you?

750
00:56:31,032 --> 00:56:34,433
You need help, Walter! You need help!
You're sick.

751
00:56:34,503 --> 00:56:38,769
"Help." Eat the pill, read the book,
see the bleeding expert.

752
00:56:38,770 --> 00:56:42,042
- Walter finally helped himself.
- Listen to yourself. This is insane.

753
00:56:42,043 --> 00:56:43,144
You're talking about a puppet.

754
00:56:43,145 --> 00:56:46,911
No, Meredith.
You're talking about a bloody puppet.

755
00:56:47,716 --> 00:56:49,946
We're talking about a miracle.

756
00:56:52,888 --> 00:56:54,698
- Who's "we," Walter?
- (EXCLAIMS)

757
00:57:03,365 --> 00:57:05,765
I know it's hard, mate. I know.

758
00:57:07,635 --> 00:57:09,925
You can't afford to get mixed up
in all of this.

759
00:57:11,338 --> 00:57:14,933
You just keep moving.
Keep moving and don't look back.

760
00:57:31,392 --> 00:57:33,360
You're right, of course.

761
00:57:35,329 --> 00:57:37,126
Walter is sick.

762
00:57:40,334 --> 00:57:45,431
But make no mistake about it, love.
I'm not going anywhere.

763
00:57:54,315 --> 00:57:56,078
I've rented a house.

764
00:57:57,284 --> 00:57:59,694
I'm taking the boys
and everything we can carry.

765
00:57:59,753 --> 00:58:03,052
I don't want you to call.
I don't want you to visit.

766
00:58:05,292 --> 00:58:09,159
If you're determined to lose your mind,
well, I can't stop you.

767
00:58:09,996 --> 00:58:14,296
But I'm not gonna let them stand there
and watch it. Not my sons.

768
00:58:20,506 --> 00:58:25,170
Insanity may play at the office,
but it's not gonna work in front of a judge.

769
00:59:23,502 --> 00:59:25,527
Why aren't you coming with us?

770
00:59:26,939 --> 00:59:29,339
Another time, mate. Another time.

771
00:59:32,978 --> 00:59:34,775
But I want to stay with you.

772
00:59:36,148 --> 00:59:39,879
You go with your mum, all right?
We'll get it sorted. You'll see.

773
00:59:39,952 --> 00:59:42,682
Everything will be good again real soon.
All right.

774
00:59:43,455 --> 00:59:44,505
- Bye.
- Let's go.

775
00:59:44,556 --> 00:59:45,606
Bye.

776
00:59:57,002 --> 00:59:58,663
I love you, Daddy.

777
01:00:01,340 --> 01:00:03,968
I love you, too, son. I love you, too.

778
01:00:05,210 --> 01:00:08,975
Go on. Off you go. Go on.

779
01:00:44,148 --> 01:00:46,708
Well, sometimes, Matt...
May I call you Matt?

780
01:00:46,784 --> 01:00:47,834
MATT: Yeah, sure.

781
01:00:47,885 --> 01:00:53,050
Sometimes, a single inspiration
just comes to you

782
01:00:53,124 --> 01:00:55,251
in the middle of the night.

783
01:00:55,326 --> 01:01:00,662
But your genius seems to hide
in a stuffed toy.

784
01:01:00,731 --> 01:01:04,497
So people have to doubt
your sanity a little.

785
01:01:04,568 --> 01:01:09,698
Well, Mozart was said to occasionally meow
like a cat,

786
01:01:09,839 --> 01:01:11,830
but he got on all right.

787
01:01:11,975 --> 01:01:13,475
Great music, don't you think?

788
01:01:14,711 --> 01:01:17,043
Walter, I want to talk about depression.

789
01:01:17,113 --> 01:01:19,445
Because the way it's been told to me,

790
01:01:19,446 --> 01:01:22,918
this whole thing started as a way for you
to deal with your mental illness.

791
01:01:22,919 --> 01:01:25,285
Well, all right.

792
01:01:25,388 --> 01:01:26,588
Well, sometimes, Matt,

793
01:01:28,391 --> 01:01:32,521
we reach a point where, in order to go on,

794
01:01:32,629 --> 01:01:35,189
we have to wipe the slate clean.

795
01:01:36,099 --> 01:01:39,529
<i>We start to see ourselves as a box
that we're trapped inside.</i>

796
01:01:39,669 --> 01:01:41,933
<i>And no matter how we try and escape,</i>

797
01:01:42,005 --> 01:01:44,496
<i>self-help, therapy, drugs,</i>

798
01:01:44,574 --> 01:01:47,236
<i>we just sink further and further down.</i>

799
01:01:47,811 --> 01:01:50,371
<i>The only way to truly break out of the box</i>

800
01:01:50,447 --> 01:01:52,547
<i>is just to get rid of it altogether.</i>

801
01:01:52,882 --> 01:01:55,851
<i>I mean, you built it in the first place.</i>

802
01:01:55,852 --> 01:01:59,655
<i>If the people around you
are breaking your spirit, who needs them?</i>

803
01:01:59,656 --> 01:02:02,124
<i>Your wife who pretends to love you,</i>

804
01:02:02,125 --> 01:02:04,093
<i>your son who can't even stand you.</i>

805
01:02:04,094 --> 01:02:06,585
<i>I mean, put them out of their misery.</i>

806
01:02:06,663 --> 01:02:08,459
<i>Starting over isn't crazy.</i>

807
01:02:10,566 --> 01:02:13,433
Crazy is being miserable

808
01:02:13,502 --> 01:02:16,232
and walking around half asleep, numb,

809
01:02:16,472 --> 01:02:19,066
<i>day after day after day.</i>

810
01:02:19,141 --> 01:02:21,200
<i>Crazy is pretending to be happy.</i>

811
01:02:22,578 --> 01:02:25,911
Pretending that the way things are

812
01:02:25,981 --> 01:02:29,382
is the way they have to be
for the rest of your bleeding life.

813
01:02:30,185 --> 01:02:32,813
<i>All the potential, hope,</i>

814
01:02:32,921 --> 01:02:34,946
<i>all that joy, feeling,</i>

815
01:02:35,023 --> 01:02:38,390
<i>all that passion
that life has sucked out of you.</i>

816
01:02:38,794 --> 01:02:40,955
Reach out, grab a hold of it

817
01:02:41,029 --> 01:02:44,965
and snatch it back
from that blood-sucking rabble.

818
01:02:47,769 --> 01:02:50,169
<i>MATT: Walter, it's good to have you here.</i>

819
01:02:50,772 --> 01:02:52,103
<i>Thank you.</i>

820
01:03:01,150 --> 01:03:02,200
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

821
01:03:02,518 --> 01:03:05,715
<i>WALTER: (AS BEAVER)
This is a picture of Walter Black,</i>

822
01:03:07,322 --> 01:03:09,619
<i>a hopelessly depressed individual</i>

823
01:03:11,592 --> 01:03:14,720
<i>who becomes the Beaver,</i>

824
01:03:14,795 --> 01:03:17,628
<i>who becomes a phenomenon.</i>

825
01:03:17,732 --> 01:03:21,582
<i>There's a lot of people out there
who are desperate enough to listen.</i>

826
01:03:22,303 --> 01:03:24,343
<i>People seem to love a train wreck</i>

827
01:03:24,805 --> 01:03:26,785
<i>when it's not happening to them.</i>

828
01:03:31,779 --> 01:03:34,270
Norah, look, we need to talk.

829
01:03:34,348 --> 01:03:35,406
Now's not a good time.

830
01:03:35,407 --> 01:03:38,084
Yeah, well, I called you, I texted you,
and I IM'd you,

831
01:03:38,085 --> 01:03:39,916
and it never seems like a good time. So...

832
01:03:39,987 --> 01:03:41,727
Maybe you should take that as a hint.

833
01:03:41,789 --> 01:03:45,384
I'm an idiot, all right?
That's not how I wanted things to turn out.

834
01:03:45,493 --> 01:03:47,984
I like you, all right?
I actually give a shit.

835
01:03:48,062 --> 01:03:51,259
You don't give a shit about me.
You don't even know me.

836
01:03:51,365 --> 01:03:53,265
Look, your brother OD'd, all right?

837
01:03:53,266 --> 01:03:55,635
But ditching your own talent,
what makes you you,

838
01:03:55,636 --> 01:03:58,972
that's not gonna bring him back.
It's just going to make you nothing.

839
01:03:58,973 --> 01:04:02,409
You stay the hell away from me.

840
01:04:02,510 --> 01:04:04,034
You and your psycho family.

841
01:04:18,758 --> 01:04:23,457
<i>Are you happy? Are you truly, truly happy?</i>

842
01:04:23,458 --> 01:04:26,165
<i>Because, Jon,
there's something lacking in all of us.</i>

843
01:04:26,166 --> 01:04:27,366
<i>A missing piece.</i>

844
01:04:27,434 --> 01:04:30,995
<i>There's a little bit of a black spot
or a dark spot.</i>

845
01:04:31,171 --> 01:04:33,821
<i>- It's that obvious?
- (AUDIENCE LAUGHING)</i>

846
01:04:33,822 --> 01:04:36,976
<i>WALTER: I'm sorry to say, Jon,
but Walter needs a little help.</i>

847
01:04:36,977 --> 01:04:39,678
<i>Because he's not too articulate
at the moment.</i>

848
01:04:39,679 --> 01:04:42,113
<i>In fact, he's not well.</i>

849
01:04:52,592 --> 01:04:55,789
Get up. Get up.

850
01:04:58,598 --> 01:05:01,032
Get up, you miserable wanker.

851
01:05:01,101 --> 01:05:04,434
You're not going to get much
out of ol' Walter.

852
01:05:04,504 --> 01:05:07,166
He's feeling a bit under the weather,
you see?

853
01:05:07,274 --> 01:05:09,366
Come on. It's a radio show.

854
01:05:09,508 --> 01:05:11,908
People can't even see the puppet.

855
01:05:11,977 --> 01:05:14,844
So why talk through the puppet?

856
01:07:23,340 --> 01:07:25,171
(RINGING)

857
01:07:28,044 --> 01:07:29,341
<i>Hello?</i>

858
01:07:29,413 --> 01:07:30,463
Mere, it's me.

859
01:07:30,714 --> 01:07:32,511
Walter, are you okay?

860
01:07:32,582 --> 01:07:33,981
<i>Yeah, look,</i>

861
01:07:34,684 --> 01:07:38,176
I can't... I can't...

862
01:07:38,255 --> 01:07:39,381
What are you doing?

863
01:07:41,425 --> 01:07:42,983
<i>What's going on?</i>

864
01:07:43,326 --> 01:07:45,191
<i>Walter? Walter, talk to me!</i>

865
01:07:46,096 --> 01:07:49,259
<i>Who are you talking to?</i>

866
01:07:49,599 --> 01:07:52,966
<i>- Hang up. You hang up right now.
- Walter?</i>

867
01:07:59,342 --> 01:08:03,244
Can your mother stitch?

868
01:08:03,447 --> 01:08:04,641
(YELLS)

869
01:08:05,382 --> 01:08:06,940
(GRUNTING)

870
01:08:17,860 --> 01:08:20,761
You'll never win.

871
01:08:32,141 --> 01:08:35,008
HENRY: I want Daddy. Where's Daddy?
MEREDITH: I know.

872
01:08:35,077 --> 01:08:37,545
HENRY: I want the Beaver.

873
01:08:39,014 --> 01:08:41,983
Are you awake?
Honey, you've got to go get Dad, all right?

874
01:08:42,151 --> 01:08:43,448
Why?

875
01:08:43,519 --> 01:08:46,579
He's not answering his phone,
and Henry won't stop crying.

876
01:08:46,655 --> 01:08:49,886
I just don't know what to do. Please.

877
01:08:49,959 --> 01:08:53,793
Come on, baby.
We're going to find Daddy soon. It's okay.

878
01:09:41,843 --> 01:09:46,940
Haven't I given you
exactly what you asked for?

879
01:09:53,922 --> 01:09:56,083
You don't need them, Walter.

880
01:10:03,064 --> 01:10:04,429
I love you.

881
01:10:08,169 --> 01:10:11,660
I'm the only one that
really, really loves you.

882
01:10:13,307 --> 01:10:19,041
And that is why
I would never let you go back.

883
01:10:23,317 --> 01:10:25,114
Never.

884
01:10:38,098 --> 01:10:40,430
I don't want to sleep anymore.

885
01:10:42,736 --> 01:10:43,786
Maybe...

886
01:10:45,539 --> 01:10:47,837
Maybe, you know,
we should work on something.

887
01:10:51,211 --> 01:10:55,238
Yeah, sure, mate. Come on.

888
01:11:08,662 --> 01:11:10,652
Walter, not like this.

889
01:11:10,730 --> 01:11:12,129
Don't do it.

890
01:11:12,231 --> 01:11:14,151
It will be worse than before. Much worse.

891
01:11:14,266 --> 01:11:17,929
Do you want to end up
a worthless, lonely piece of shit?

892
01:11:19,872 --> 01:11:21,931
You're nothing without me, Walter.

893
01:11:22,842 --> 01:11:23,892
Nothing!

894
01:11:24,677 --> 01:11:26,357
I'm the only part of you that works.

895
01:11:26,846 --> 01:11:28,780
(BLADE WHIRRING)

896
01:11:34,687 --> 01:11:36,348
I'm sorry.

897
01:11:41,427 --> 01:11:43,258
(WALTER SCREAMING)

898
01:11:51,871 --> 01:11:54,897
Walter! How about Henry, your kid?
You remember him?

899
01:11:55,741 --> 01:11:57,140
Walter!

900
01:12:00,246 --> 01:12:01,372
Dad?

901
01:12:01,373 --> 01:12:06,885
BP's dropping. Don't touch the tourniquet
until he's on the table.

902
01:12:06,886 --> 01:12:08,911
It's the only reason he still has a pulse.

903
01:12:09,922 --> 01:12:11,902
<i>(EXIT MUSIC FOR A FILM PLAYING)</i>

904
01:12:15,326 --> 01:12:16,987
<i>(SINGING) Wake</i>

905
01:12:18,296 --> 01:12:20,457
<i>From your sleep</i>

906
01:12:23,134 --> 01:12:29,801
<i>The drying of your tears</i>

907
01:12:30,742 --> 01:12:35,941
<i>Today we escape</i>

